Anatomy Of A Modern Hit

What Makes a Great Song?

Written by Jaya Dhariwal and Zach Barsamian

Project Website

Click here!

Project Goal

In this project, we aim to determine what metrics can be best used to predict the success of a song. Are the most popular songs topping the charts every week? Getting the most music video views on Youtube?

For this milestone, our aim is to specifically see the correlation between different features of each song. We look at the top 200 weekly songs on Spotify, specifically at the average popularity of a song and how long that popularity persists. Then, we look at the music video views of a different set of songs on Youtube. This provides a different angle to measure online popularity that we can compare to chart performance. Finally, we look at Grammy nomination data. We take a Grammy nomination to be one of the highest tangible success metrics a song can achieve and explore potential relationships between a songs online popularity and its critical reception.

Is music now an entirely digital medium? Are there other significant factors at play that will impede our predictive capability? Find out below.

Data Set 1

Describing the set

We obtained our first dataset from a web scrape of Spotify's Charts website. We scraped 418 weeks worth of data for the top 200 songs by streams on Spotify, every week, starting with the last full week of 2016 and going to the last full week of 2024. The scraper is linked here, but the basic methodology was to use Selenium's Chrome webdriver to open an automated Chrome browser and navigate to the Spotify Charts top 200 weekly page. Starting at the earliest available table, we parse the 200 table rows on that week's page, and then navigate to the next week and repeat that process 418 times.

After loading and tidying the DataFrame, we are able to analyze the data. Using The Weeknd's Starboy as an example, we see how the scraped streaming data matches up to the actual streaming numbers shown on the Spotify website. Then, we use a cluster model to analyze archetypes within the chart data on Spotify. Later, we see how these archetypes match up to other metrics like Youtube views and Grammy nominations.

Next, we want to add a rank column for a more continuous measurement of week-by-week popularity. The songs are already in order for each week because the Charts page ranked them from 1-200, but we didn't include this column in our scrape, so we have to construct it manually.

In[9]:
merged_df['rank'] = merged_df.groupby('date_week')['weekly_streams'].rank(method='min', ascending=False).astype(int)

Right after we added the rank column, we realized something was wrong: in the Charts data, occasionally a row is just skipped, and the index increments by two instead of one. This meant that a few weeks were missing a few songs, completely at random. If we had included rank in our scrape, this wouldn't have been an issue for us. However, due to our disastrous lack of foresight, manually reconstructing the rank column meant ignoring the occasional skip that happens in the real data.

In short, we had to locate these skips manually. We looked at all the 200 rank songs in the DataFrame; each week that was missing was a week that had <200 songs, and would not show up in this view. For each of those weeks, we scrolled through the corresponding Charts page to find the skipped rank/s. Then, we added a pair of {song name: week it needs to be incremented} to the dictionary below, and moved on to the next absent week.

When that was done, we wrote the code below to iterate through the dictionary. It locates each song, increments it and all higher ranked songs from the same week by one, and then moves onto the next song. Once finished, every week has a 200th ranked song, and the ranks in our data now perfectly match the ranks from the site.

Now we want to consider what conclusions we can draw from this set. We can't use the streaming figures for cumulative measurement, as seen by the Starboy example. However, we look at how popular a song is relative to other songs, and how that metric varies over time. To do this, we need to create two new metrics. The mean rank of a song will represent it's relative popularity for the time it was on the charts. The longevity will measure the number of weeks it charted.

We predict that, based on these features, songs will fall into distinct categories that can roughly be considered their "overall popularity". Specifically, we think that at least three distinct categories will emerge: massive hits, average hits, and "tiktok songs". For example, some songs that spend a while on the chart might peak with a really low (good) rank, but then rise to the mid-100s for the main duration of their stay. These "tiktok" songs would have high longevity and high mean rank, meaning that although they charted for a while, they can't be considered as popular as songs with similar longevity and a consistently lower rank--average or massive hits.

To test this hypothesis, we ran an unsupervised k-means cluster model. Four random original centroids are created within the dataset, and all other data points are assinged a cluster based on the closest centroid by euclidian distance. The centroids are then updated to the mean of each cluster, and the assignment process is repeated. This goes on until the centroids stop moving, at which point four clusters have been found based on similarity.

In[16]:
#for each artist, a) how much time did they spend on the charts, and
#b) what was their mean rank throughout this time
song_features_df = merged_df.groupby(['title', 'artist']).agg(
    longevity=('date_week', 'nunique'),
    mean_rank=('rank', 'mean')
).reset_index()

#features dataframe to train cluster model
features_df = song_features_df[['longevity', 'mean_rank']]

#initialize the scaler and normalize features
scaler = StandardScaler()
features_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(features_df)

#running kmeans model with 4 original centroids, choosing the same
# random points every time.
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init='auto')

# Add the cluster labels back to the original DataFrame
song_features_df['cluster'] = kmeans.fit_predict(features_scaled)

#reverse-scales the final centroids to make their values interpretable
original_centroids = scaler.inverse_transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)

#dictionary to mapping cluster numbers to more descriptive archetype names
label_map = {
    0: "Album Cuts",
    1: "Brief Hits",
    2: "Popular Hits",
    3: "Massive Hits"
}

#mapping more descriptive archetype names to cluster labels
song_features_df['archetype'] = song_features_df['cluster'].map(label_map)

As you can see, our hypothesis was somewhat supported. There is a standout category of massive hits with extremely long longevity and an average mean rank. The next cluster of popular hits has about a third the longevity, but a slightly lower mean rank. Then, instead of there being a category with high longevity and high mean rank--the "tiktok song" category that we predicted--the other two categories are just songs that spent relatively little time on the charts, separated by an average and a low mean rank.

While the unsupervised cluster model was useful for analysis of the Spotify chart data, it is difficult to generalize and connect it to our Youtube views data or our Grammy data. For our other future models, we are inclined to use longevity and mean rank to direclty train a classification model. However, the cluster model provides a useful analysis of the different archetypes for song popularity that you see in the data from one, significant streaming platform.

Data Set 2

Describing the set

We obtained our second data set, linked here, from huggingface.co. It presents over 24,000 of the most-listened-to music videos from the last decade. The variables measured include song, artist, year, genre and views. This data was obtained from a Youtube webscrape sourced from Wikidata.

For this dataset, our aim was to compare a new online popularity metric, music video views, to an artists success. Although it is not holistic, we use music video popularity as a new metric to represent engagement on social platforms. The engagement on Youtube would ideally be similar to chart popularity, however, Youtube video views are not indicative of how popular a song is on the radio. Since watching a music video takes more active engagement, while listening tends to be more passive, we could think of views as a measure of that active popularity. Additionally, these views are cumulative, and weekly chart measurements are not. This means that we now have two interesting perspectives on digital popularity, but they are not perfectly compatible with each other.

Data Frame 3

Describing the set

Our third data set, linked here , which we obtained from Kaggle, presents all grammy nominations and winners from 1958-2024. The variables are year, award show, type of award, song, nominee, and win/loss. This data was obtained from a webscrape on the Grammy website and filled in missing data with information from Wikipedia (linked below).

We plan to use this data to compare popularity on digital platforms to performance on stage at the Grammys. This dataset required a lot of cleaning up, as we only wanted to look at song nominations and awards, not artist nor album nominations/awards. We planned for a song's Grammy nominations and wins to be a tangible metric that may depend but does not rely on a songs popularity. With a more supposedly "holistic" measurement of success, we can see how a songs digital popularity measures up to its critical reception. We suspect to find that as a song's music video views and chart popularity increases, the likelihood of winning a Grammy award also increases. How critical are these accolades, really?

Grammy and Song Features

Then, we do a left join on the song features data frame. The reason we did a left join and not an inner join is because there are songs that do not appear in the grammy data set because they had zero nominations. These missing values are still important data, because they indicate (very roughly) poorer critical reception. We fill in the missing data in the new dataframe with 0, as a missing value in this case indicates 0 nominations and as a result 0 Grammy wins.

In[32]:
grammy_and_chart = pd.merge(song_features_df, grammy_df, on='Song_clean', how='left') #left join on song features

Future Analysis

From this analysis, we can see the rough correlation of a song's views on Youtube, chart performance on Spotify, and success at the Grammys. However, it is hard to tangibly join all of this analysis. In the future, we wish to build 2 regression models, training on each our digital metric datasets and predicting Grammy success. The goal of this dual-model strategy will be to determine which online popularity metric is the most "official" indication of a hit song.

Model 1: Longevity & Rank To Predict Nominations

Our first model will be a classification model that takes the average longevity and rank of a song and predicts if it will be nominated or not. Our dependent variable (y) is Grammy nominations, and our independent variables (x) will be longevity and rank.

First, to justify building this model, we can see that there is a correlation between longevity and nominations. For example, below we can see the average longevity doubles in the nominated data set versus the not-nominated set.

In[49]:
grammy_and_chart.groupby('if nominated')[['longevity', 'mean_rank']].mean()
